<HEAD>De Beers Tightens Grip on Diamond Market With Soviet Deal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By COTTEN TIMBERLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The <LOCATION>Soviet Union</LOCATION> will get more badly needed
foreign hard currency by selling its rough diamonds exclusively
through the South African giant De Beers in a five-year
multibillion-dollar agreement.
   The company is advancing the Soviets <MONEY>$1 billion</MONEY> against future
diamond sales, said officials who announced the agreement on
<DATE>Wednesday</DATE>.
   The <LOCATION>Soviet Union</LOCATION>, among the world's largest diamond producers,
reached the deal with De Beers because it wanted to sell a huge
stockpile of diamonds without disrupting the market, De Beers said.
   The <LOCATION>Soviet Union</LOCATION> had refused to deal directly with the South
African company because of apartheid, but now is willing to openly
do business with De Beers' new Swiss arm, De <ORGANIZATION>Beers Centenary AG</ORGANIZATION>.
   South Africa-based De <ORGANIZATION>Beers Consolidated Mines Ltd.</ORGANIZATION>, controlled
by the Oppenheimer family of <LOCATION>South Africa</LOCATION>, established the
publicly-held Swiss company in <DATE>May</DATE>.
   De <ORGANIZATION>Beers Centenary</ORGANIZATION> said in a statement that it reached the
agreement with Glavalmazzoloto of the <ORGANIZATION>USSR</ORGANIZATION> for the exclusive export
and sale of the <LOCATION>Soviet Union</LOCATION>'s diamond production.
   Glavalmazzoloto is the main administration for precious metals
and diamonds under the <LOCATION>Soviet Union</LOCATION>'s council of ministers, De
Beers said.
   It said its Luxembourg-based subsidiary, <ORGANIZATION>Centenary Holdings SA</ORGANIZATION>,
has agreed to make a secured advance of <MONEY>$1 billion</MONEY> to
Glavalmazzoloto against future diamond deliveries.
   Repayment would be made over five years beginning in <DATE>November</DATE>,
it said.
   <PERSON>Nicholas Oppenheimer</PERSON>, deputy chairman of <ORGANIZATION>De Beers Centenary</ORGANIZATION>,
said as a result of the agreement that the <LOCATION>Soviet Union</LOCATION>, at a time
of ``considerable financial strain,'' was assured ``a steady flow
of funds from diamonds'' during the life of the contract.
   Company officials estimated the contract could be worth as much
as <MONEY>$5 billion</MONEY>.
   <LOCATION>Moscow</LOCATION> has been seeking foreign credit as it tries to bring
market-oriented reform to an economy plagued by shortages.
   The Soviet diamond stockpile will be held at De Beers'
London-based marketing arm, the <ORGANIZATION>Central Selling Organization</ORGANIZATION>, as
collateral for the <MONEY>$1 billion</MONEY> advance, De Beers said.
   The organization, a 57-year-old cartel, has the financial
resources to hold large stocks of diamonds, which is how it keeps
the market stable.
   Although De Beers said it had had no direct contact with the
<LOCATION>Soviet Union</LOCATION> since <DATE>1963</DATE>, diamond experts say De Beers already sells
most of the <LOCATION>Soviet Union</LOCATION>'s West-bound diamonds.
   All the world's major diamond producers, including <LOCATION>Botswana</LOCATION>,
<LOCATION>Australia</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Tanzania</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Zaire</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Namibia</LOCATION>, have sales contracts with
De Beers Centenary. The <ORGANIZATION>Central Selling Organization</ORGANIZATION>, as a result,
markets <PERCENT>80 percent</PERCENT> of the world's rough diamond production of some
100 million carats.
   The organization had sales of <MONEY>$4.09 billion</MONEY> last year.
   Large-scale diamond mining began in the <LOCATION>Soviet Union</LOCATION> in the
<DATE>1950s</DATE> and is concentrated in the <LOCATION>Yakutia</LOCATION> region of <LOCATION>North Eastern
Siberia</LOCATION>, De Beers said. The <LOCATION>Soviet Union</LOCATION> doesn't disclose the value
of its output.
