<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAR 93 / International Company News: De Beers restricts dividend cut
to 29%
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP GAWITH
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   JOHANNESBURG
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
DE BEERS, the South African company which dominates the world diamond
market, yesterday pleased investors by holding the cut in its <DATE>1992</DATE> dividend
to <MONEY>29 per cent</MONEY> - to <MONEY>79.1 cents</MONEY> from <MONEY>112.1 cents</MONEY> - after announcing a 35 per
cent fall in earnings for the year.
Many analysts had predicted a much larger reduction in the payout. The
company's shares climbed after the announcement, closing at R68.85 (Dollars
21.61) - nearly 4 per cent up for the day.
Analysts agreed the size of the dividend cut indicated that De Beers'
financial health and the general state of the world diamond industry were
better than the market had expected.
<PERSON>Mr Julian Ogilvie Thompson</PERSON>, chairman, said the fall in earnings reflected
the difficult second half. Attributable profits at De Beers and Centenary,
its offshore arm, fell by 49 per cent in the second half, compared with a 26
per cent fall in first.
Pre-tax profits on the diamond account fell by 20 per cent to Dollars 644m
from <ORGANIZATION>Dollars</ORGANIZATION> 801m in <DATE>1991</DATE> reflecting the impact of the quotas.
Net interest income slumped 79 per cent to Dollars 30m from <ORGANIZATION>Dollars</ORGANIZATION> 141m.
This was due to lower cash balances after the company bought up diamond
supplies that bypassed the Central Selling Organisation (CSO), the De Beers
company that trades 80 per cent of world rough diamond output.
<PERSON>Mr Ogilvie Thompson</PERSON> estimated that Dollars 500m to Dollars 600m worth of
diamonds which bypassed the <ORGANIZATION>CSO</ORGANIZATION> - both legal and illegal - had come from
<LOCATION>Angola</LOCATION> during the year, of which De Beers had bought about two-thirds.
Attributable earnings fell to <ORGANIZATION>Dollars</ORGANIZATION> 491m from <ORGANIZATION>Dollars</ORGANIZATION> 759m, while equity
accounted earnings fell to <ORGANIZATION>Dollars</ORGANIZATION> 757m from Dollars 1.07bn. Earnings per
share, excluding retained earnings of associates, fell <MONEY>35 per cent</MONEY> to <MONEY>129
cents</MONEY> from <MONEY>200 cents</MONEY>.
