<LP>
   LONDON (AP) -- Angola, a major diamond producing nation,
is re-entering the De Beers Centenary AG diamond powerhouse,
ending a five-year absence, De Beers said.
   Endiama, the Angolan state diamond company, and De Beers
agreed to re-establish their relationship, De Beers said.
Angola has been marketing its diamonds independently since
1985, after civil war prompted De Beers to pull out, a De
Beers spokesman said.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Under the agreement, De Beer's London-based <ORGANIZATION>Central
Selling Organization</ORGANIZATION> will market <LOCATION>Angola</LOCATION>'s diamonds from its
Cuango region, or about three-quarters of the country's
annual production of one million carats, the De Beers
spokesman said.
   De Beers also will provide <ORGANIZATION>Endiama</ORGANIZATION> with a <MONEY>$50 million</MONEY> loan
to increase production in the <LOCATION>Cuango</LOCATION> area, and an additional
<MONEY>$50 million</MONEY> over the next five years to develop other diamond
sources in <LOCATION>Angola</LOCATION>.
   About <PERCENT>80%</PERCENT> of the world's annual diamond production is
sorted and sold by De Beers's <ORGANIZATION>Central Selling Organization</ORGANIZATION>,
which had diamond sales of <MONEY>$4.1 billion</MONEY> in <DATE>1989</DATE>.
</TEXT>
