<HEAD>Angola Re-enters Diamond Cartel</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   <LOCATION>Angola</LOCATION>, a major diamond producing nation, is
re-entering the De Beers diamond cartel after five years, De Beers
said <DATE>Thursday</DATE>.
   <ORGANIZATION>Endiama</ORGANIZATION>, the Angolan state diamond company, and <ORGANIZATION>De Beers
Centenary AG</ORGANIZATION> on <DATE>Thursday</DATE> signed an agreement re-establishing their
relationship, De Beers said.
   Under the agreement, De Beer's <ORGANIZATION>Central Selling Organization</ORGANIZATION> will
market <LOCATION>Angola</LOCATION>'s diamonds from its Cuango region, or about
three-quarters of the country's annual production of one million
carats, said <PERSON>Roger van Eeghen</PERSON>, a De Beers spokesman.
   De Beers also will provide <ORGANIZATION>Endiama</ORGANIZATION> with a <MONEY>$50 million</MONEY> loan to
increase production in the <LOCATION>Cuango</LOCATION> area, and another <MONEY>$50 million</MONEY>
over the next five years to develop other diamond sources in
<LOCATION>Angola</LOCATION>.
   <LOCATION>Angola</LOCATION> had been marketing its diamonds independently since <DATE>1985</DATE>
after civil war prompted De Beers to pull out, <ORGANIZATION>Van Eeghen</ORGANIZATION> said.
   About <PERCENT>80 percent</PERCENT> of the world's annual diamond production is
sorted and sold by the London-based <ORGANIZATION>Central Selling Organization</ORGANIZATION>.
It had diamond sales of <MONEY>$4.1 billion</MONEY> in <DATE>1989</DATE>.
</TEXT>
