<HEAD>De Beers To Raise Rough Gem Diamond Prices 5.5 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   De <ORGANIZATION>Beers Consolidated Mines Ltd.</ORGANIZATION> said <DATE>Wednesday</DATE> it
will raise the prices of rough gem diamonds sold through its
Central Selling Organization by an average <PERCENT>5.5 percent</PERCENT> effective
<DATE>Monday</DATE>.
   Vigorous consumer demand and a need to keep prices in line with
global inflation prompted the rise, said De Beers spokesman <PERSON>Andrew
Lamont</PERSON>.
   De Beers pushed prices up <PERCENT>15.5 percent</PERCENT> in its last increase in
<DATE>March 1989</DATE>.
   The organization's sales were down <PERCENT>2 percent</PERCENT> at <MONEY>$4.09 billion</MONEY>
last year and are expected to be flat this year.
   Rough diamonds yielding polished diamonds of one carat and less
have been selling at a premium in the open diamond bourses not run
by the <ORGANIZATION>Central Selling Organization</ORGANIZATION> for the last several months,
reflecting the strong demand, De Beers said.
   Polished diamonds currently fetching between <MONEY>$400</MONEY> and <MONEY>$3,500</MONEY> a
carat, are experiencing particularly strong demand, and will bear
the brunt of the price increase, <PERSON>Lamont</PERSON> said.
   De Beers doesn't disclose its prices, which vary considerably.
The wholesale price of the highest grade one-carat gem is about
<MONEY>$16,000</MONEY>.
   The organization sorts and values about <PERCENT>80 percent</PERCENT> of the
world's rough diamonds before selling them to wholesalers at
regular sales called ``sights.''
</TEXT>
