<HEAD>Announces Discovery of World's Largest Uncut Diamond</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto JOH1</NOTE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The De Beers diamond firm has
announced the discovery of an egg-sized, 599-carat diamond and said
it is currently the world's largest uncut diamond with an estimated
cut value of <MONEY>$30 million</MONEY>.
   Officials of the South African company said the white diamond,
dubbed ``The Big Rock,'' was found at a mine near <LOCATION>Pretoria</LOCATION> in <DATE>July
1986</DATE>, but its discovery was kept secret to all but a handful of De
Beers executives.
   De Beers' chairman <PERSON>Julian Thompson</PERSON> announced the find at the
firm's 100th anniversary banquet in <LOCATION>Kimberly</LOCATION> <DATE>Friday</DATE> <TIME>night</TIME>.
   ``It's a perfect blue-white color,'' said South African gem
expert <PERSON>Gaby Tolkowski</PERSON>, who will cut and polish the stone.
   There have been larger raw diamonds uncovered previously, but
they were cut into smaller gems.
   The <DATE>1988</DATE> <ORGANIZATION>Guinness Book of World Records</ORGANIZATION> recorded the <PERSON>Cullinan</PERSON>
diamond as the world's largest uncut diamond ever found. It was
discovered in <DATE>1905</DATE> near <LOCATION>Pretoria</LOCATION> and weighed 3,106 carats, or more
than 1.25 pounds.
   The <PERSON>Cullinan</PERSON> was cut into 105 stones, including the 530.2-carat
Star of <LOCATION>Africa</LOCATION>, the world's largest known cut diamond, according to
<ORGANIZATION>Guinness</ORGANIZATION>. The Star of <LOCATION>Africa</LOCATION> is the centerpiece of the British
royal scepter.
   In its cut form, the ``Big Rock'' is expected to be about 350
carats and sell for an estimated <MONEY>$30 million</MONEY>, the company said.
   <ORGANIZATION>DeBeers</ORGANIZATION> is the world's largest diamond company and controls an
estimated <PERCENT>80 percent</PERCENT> of the world's diamond production through its
central selling organization in <LOCATION>London</LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
